04998nam a22006735i 9780228012665DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280126657 a10.1515/97802280126652doi  a(DE-B1597)657217  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aG743b.Q813 2022eb 7aHIS0510002bisacsh04an-gl---ar------1 ade Quervain, Alfred, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAcross Greenland's Ice Cap :bThe Remarkable Swiss Scientific Expedition of 1912 /cAlfred de Quervain. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b65 colour photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface to This Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAlfred De Quervain’s Scientific Legacy: An Appraisal -- tAbout The Colour Plates -- tA Note on the Text -- tTranslators’ Foreword -- tAuthor’s Preface -- tPlans and Preparations -- tThe Sea Voyage -- tOld Friends -- tThe Dog School -- tNorthward With The Fox -- tCrossing The Rock Border -- tTo The Inland Ice Lake -- tOver The Top Of Greenland’s Firn Region -- tEastern Mountains Ahead! -- tTo Angmagssalik By Umiak -- tWith The Eastern Eskimos -- tReturn Via Iceland: Scientific Results -- tThe Summer Of The Western Party -- tA Winter In Greenland -- tAbout The Authors, Translators, And Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs polar exploration reached its zenith, and in the same month that Captain Robert Falcon Scott perished in Antarctica, four young scientists from Zurich took ship for Greenland. Though they had little previous experience of arctic travel, their ambition was to achieve the first west-to-east crossing of the northern hemisphere’s largest ice cap, making scientific observations along the way.Few outside Switzerland have heard of this expedition or its leader, the meteorologist Alfred de Quervain, in spite of its success. In thirty-one days in the summer of 1912, the party sledded across 640 kilometres of untracked snow and ice. Nobody died or fell into a crevasse, although there were some near misses. The voyage was more than a well-executed feat of arctic travel: de Quervain and his colleagues collected data still used today by scientists researching the effects of climate change on Greenland’s ice cap. De Quervain’s popular account of his adventures, published in German in 1914, is both a minor classic of exploration literature and a sympathetic portrayal of life in Greenland’s remote coastal settlements in the early twentieth century.Published to coincide with the expedition’s 110th anniversary, Across Greenland’s Ice Cap includes the explorer’s original text, translated into English by his daughter and son-in-law; a historical and biographical introduction by Martin Hood; reflections on the journey’s scientific legacy by the geographers Andreas Vieli and Martin Lüthi; and a treasure trove of hand-tinted lantern slides reproduced in full colour.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aScientific expeditionszGreenland. 7aHISTORY / Expeditions & Discoveries.2bisacsh  aEskimo life.  aGreenland.  aPolar exploration.  aSwitzerland.  aadventure.  aclimate change.  adog-sledding.  aethnography.  aglaciology.  ahistory.  ameteorology.  aphotography.  ascience.1 aHood, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLüthi, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMercanton, Paul-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStolberg, August, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca